of what's going on.

00:24:49.870 --> 00:24:52.610
The next most obvious thing is
these kind of dark-colored

00:24:52.610 --> 00:24:54.660
transit lines that you see
running horizontally and

00:24:54.660 --> 00:24:55.800
vertically.

00:24:55.800 --> 00:24:58.400
And also, you can see the little
dotted ferry lines in

00:24:58.400 --> 00:24:59.780
the top-right corner here.

00:24:59.780 --> 00:25:02.050
So again, we don't really
need this information.

00:25:02.050 --> 00:25:05.310
We'll get rid of that, too.

00:25:05.310 --> 00:25:08.130
And now we've got a fairly
minimal map.

00:25:08.130 --> 00:25:10.355
I think right now, we're
probably done with removing

00:25:10.355 --> 00:25:11.930
the information.

00:25:11.930 --> 00:25:13.825
So now it's time to refine
the information

00:25:13.825 --> 00:25:15.330
that we've got left.

00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:17.820
Now the water is looking pretty
heavy at the moment.

00:25:17.820 --> 00:25:19.840
I think that's probably
the main colored

00:25:19.840 --> 00:25:20.650
element on the screen.

00:25:20.650 --> 00:25:22.280
This is drawing our attention.

00:25:22.280 --> 00:25:24.140
So we don't really want that.

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:26.850
I quite liked what Scott did
earlier, which was to remove

00:25:26.850 --> 00:25:28.690
the water and change
it to white.

00:25:28.690 --> 00:25:31.280
So I think let's do that, and
that will give us a nice,

00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:35.310
clean background canvas
to work from.

00:25:35.310 --> 00:25:38.050
And so this is immediately
looking a lot better.

00:25:38.050 --> 00:25:40.900
And this introduces the new
feature that we've got today

00:25:40.900 --> 00:25:43.730
to recolor things directly.

00:25:43.730 --> 00:25:46.110
So now this park thing's
bugging me.

00:25:46.110 --> 00:25:48.040
So let's bring the
parks back again.

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:50.190
I don't think we'd want them to
be a fully prominent green.

00:25:50.190 --> 00:25:52.750
So we'll just use a quiet,
subtle gray, because we want

00:25:52.750 --> 00:25:55.400
them there for context and
orientation of the map, but

00:25:55.400 --> 00:25:58.590
not to be something that
you really notice.

00:25:58.590 --> 00:26:01.720
So here's the parks added
back in again.

00:26:01.720 --> 00:26:03.500
SCOTT SHAWCROFT: As you can see,
we just have individual

00:26:03.500 --> 00:26:06.890
styles on the left
side, typically.

00:26:06.890 --> 00:26:09.120
The expectation is that we're
adding those to the

00:26:09.120 --> 00:26:10.280
list that we have.

00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:13.700
And so to turn on parks, we
don't need to go back and

00:26:13.700 --> 00:26:17.060
change the POI visibility off.

00:26:17.060 --> 00:26:20.670
We can simply add another
style that selects our

00:26:20.670 --> 00:26:25.360
poi.park, which is just our
parts and just their geometry,

00:26:25.360 --> 00:26:28.030
and then turn them on in
addition to coloring them.

00:26:28.030 --> 00:26:30.000
JONAH JONES: And again, it's
important to note, as Scott

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.730
said, we are bringing just the
geometry back in here.

00:26:32.730 --> 00:26:35.030
If we'd forgotten to include
that, then we'd have brought

00:26:35.030 --> 00:26:37.640
the labels back in, which
isn't what we wanted.

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:39.930
So this is now looking
fairly good.

00:26:39.930 --> 00:26:43.110
The obvious last thing to
remove now is the roads.

00:26:43.110 --> 00:26:45.080
Now we want to keep the roads
on the map because they're

00:26:45.080 --> 00:26:47.300
good for, again, orientation,
but we don't

00:26:47.300 --> 00:26:48.280
really need the colors.

00:26:48.280 --> 00:26:50.500
And I don't think we need a
distinction between the stroke

00:26:50.500 --> 00:26:51.145
and the fill here.

00:26:51.145 --> 00:26:52.860
It's just adding visual noise.

00:26:52.860 --> 00:26:55.720
So let's simplify these.

00:26:55.720 --> 00:26:59.200
And we've just given them a
kind of grey fill here.

00:26:59.200 --> 00:27:01.110
So this is now nearly done.

00:27:01.110 --> 00:27:05.010
I think probably the last thing
we should do here is the

00:27:05.010 --> 00:27:07.810
roads are still looking just
that tiny little bit too

00:27:07.810 --> 00:27:09.550
heavy, still a little bit fat.

00:27:09.550 --> 00:27:12.030
So we can refine these a little
bit further with the

00:27:12.030 --> 00:27:16.220
new width control that we've
announced today and make them

00:27:16.220 --> 00:27:17.890
a bit thinner.

00:27:17.890 --> 00:27:20.190
SCOTT SHAWCROFT: Yeah, so as
you can see here, we're

00:27:20.190 --> 00:27:22.060
setting the weight of the three

00:27:22.060 --> 00:27:23.800
different types of roads.

00:27:23.800 --> 00:27:26.740
What's interesting is that we're
setting the arterials

00:27:26.740 --> 00:27:28.630
and the locals to
the same weight.

00:27:28.630 --> 00:27:33.350
The reason this doesn't screw up
our hierarchy where we want

00:27:33.350 --> 00:27:35.920
the highways to be fatter than
the arterials, and the

00:27:35.920 --> 00:27:39.750
arterials to be fatter than the
local roads is because in

00:27:39.750 --> 00:27:43.280
San Francisco, arterials are
typically separated by a

00:27:43.280 --> 00:27:46.650
median, which means we actually
draw two lines next

00:27:46.650 --> 00:27:50.690
to each other and causes them
to look fat, even though the

00:27:50.690 --> 00:27:54.130
weights are identical to the
weight of the local road.

00:27:54.130 --> 00:27:56.300
JONAH JONES: And this may not
be the case everywhere.

00:27:56.300 --> 00:27:59.000
In different parts of the world,
it could be that the

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:04.020
arterials are done as one road
instead of two, in which case

00:28:04.020 --> 00:28:06.250
the arterial road thing we've
got here would probably need

00:28:06.250 --> 00:28:10.350
to be 1 or 0.75, or something
like that to maintain that

00:28:10.350 --> 00:28:11.600
sense of hierarchy.

00:28:11.600 --> 00:28:13.450
But for San Francisco
here, this is

00:28:13.450 --> 00:28:14.450
looking great, actually.

00:28:14.450 --> 00:28:19.640
So I think we can add our dogs
and cats data back again.

00:28:19.640 --> 00:28:21.830
And this is looking
pretty good.

00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:25.620
There's one problem here, which
is that this is probably

00:28:25.620 --> 00:28:27.960
fine to most of you, but maybe
a couple of you in the

00:28:27.960 --> 00:28:31.510
audience are seeing something
a bit more like this.

00:28:31.510 --> 00:28:34.710
This is what you'll see if
you're colorblind, where reds

00:28:34.710 --> 00:28:36.400
and greens, distinguishing
between them can

00:28:36.400 --> 00:28:37.650
be a bit of a problem.

00:28:37.650 --> 00:28:41.470
So there's a few different
approaches you could use to

00:28:41.470 --> 00:28:42.850
combat this.

00:28:42.850 --> 00:28:45.310
One good one is to just change
the brightness of

00:28:45.310 --> 00:28:46.960
the red and the green.

00:28:46.960 --> 00:28:49.250
We actually do this on
our traffic layer.

00:28:49.250 --> 00:28:51.990
Another one would be to change
the shapes, so maybe the red

00:28:51.990 --> 00:28:53.830
things would be triangles
and the green

00:28:53.830 --> 00:28:55.230
things would be circles.

00:28:55.230 --> 00:28:57.860
We actually considered using
cute little cats and dogs on

00:28:57.860 --> 00:28:59.625
the map, but we thought
that was a bit cheesy.

00:28:59.625 --> 00:29:03.470
So for now we'll just give
it a nice Google I/O

00:29:03.470 --> 00:29:05.250
themed set of colors.

00:29:05.250 --> 00:29:06.640
And there we have it.

00:29:06.640 --> 00:29:08.610
We've got nice map
of San Francisco.

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:11.110
We can clearly visualize
the data on top.

00:29:11.110 --> 00:29:12.230
It's taken us about
10 minutes.

00:29:12.230 --> 00:29:13.540
That's not bad.

00:29:13.540 --> 00:29:16.310
So the next stage would
be to check the

00:29:16.310 --> 00:29:17.960
different zooms and regions.

00:29:17.960 --> 00:29:20.285
But something I didn't mention
before is there's actually a

00:29:20.285 --> 00:29:21.560
clever little trick here
than we can do.

00:29:21.560 --> 00:29:24.780
So I'll give you Scott back
to introduce you that.

00:29:24.780 --> 00:29:25.830
SCOTT SHAWCROFT: Thank you.

00:29:25.830 --> 00:29:28.000
So Jonah and I work
on Google Maps.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.590
And because we work on Google
Maps, we have to think about

00:29:30.590 --> 00:29:32.610
everyone in the entire world.

00:29:32.610 --> 00:29:33.290
That's a good thing.

00:29:33.290 --> 00:29:33.940
We like that.

00:29:33.940 --> 00:29:36.450
But it makes it really hard
to get a design that works

00:29:36.450 --> 00:29:38.660
everywhere.

00:29:38.660 --> 00:29:41.290
In addition to that, we have
to check every zoom level.

00:29:41.290 --> 00:29:44.640
We have 20 different zoom levels
that we have a map on,

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:47.600
and a design that works
for zoom 4 may not

00:29:47.600 --> 00:29:49.530
work for zoom 17.

00:29:49.530 --> 00:29:53.990
However, you guys have a better
idea of what your users

00:29:53.990 --> 00:29:58.180
want from your map, so you can
restrict both the zooms that

00:29:58.180 --> 00:30:01.570
the user looks at, and the
places in the world that they

00:30:01.570 --> 00:30:03.200
can see on your map.

00:30:03.200 --> 00:30:06.660
So how do you do that?

00:30:06.660 --> 00:30:10.770
To restrict the zoom, you simply
set the min zoom and

00:30:10.770 --> 00:30:13.140
the max zoom on the
map options before

00:30:13.140 --> 00:30:14.540
you create your map.

00:30:14.540 --> 00:30:18.640
Here you can see I've used a
variable for my default zoom

00:30:18.640 --> 00:30:20.920
so that if I want to change
my default, it's easy.

00:30:23.450 --> 00:30:27.780
That's what the zoom option on
the object is, is also the

00:30:27.780 --> 00:30:28.810
default zoom.

00:30:28.810 --> 00:30:31.080
And then I'm just allowing
two more zoom levels

00:30:31.080 --> 00:30:32.620
in addition to that.

00:30:32.620 --> 00:30:35.110
So that's restricting zoom.

00:30:35.110 --> 00:30:38.210
Restricting the center is
a little bit trickier.

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:41.350
What I have here is a
LatLngBounds at the top that

00:30:41.350 --> 00:30:44.180
the center of the view port
will be restricted to.

00:30:44.180 --> 00:30:47.750
In our example, this is a rough
bounding box for the

00:30:47.750 --> 00:30:49.340
data that we're showing.

00:30:49.340 --> 00:30:56.290
And then on every center changed
event callback, we

00:30:56.290 --> 00:30:59.750
take the center of the map, we
see if it's in those bounds,

00:30:59.750 --> 00:31:02.140
and if it is in those
bounds, we're done.

00:31:02.140 --> 00:31:04.750
Otherwise we need to move
it back into the bounds.

00:31:04.750 --> 00:31:08.870
And we do that by capping the
latitude and the longitude and

00:31:08.870 --> 00:31:12.910
then resetting the center
of our map.

00:31:12.910 --> 00:31:15.770
So now that we've restricted
the zoom in the center, we

00:31:15.770 --> 00:31:18.470
know where people are
going to look at.

00:31:18.470 --> 00:31:21.710
Jonah's design was only done
for zoom 13, so let's check

00:31:21.710 --> 00:31:25.520
the other two zooms that we're
going to allow them to see.

00:31:25.520 --> 00:31:27.560
So this is zoom 14.

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:28.920
It looks good.

00:31:28.920 --> 00:31:31.270
There's nothing that
we didn't expect.

00:31:31.270 --> 00:31:34.440
You can see the nice Golden Gate
Park there running across

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:37.130
the screen, along with the
Presidio above it.

00:31:37.130 --> 00:31:38.300
I think it looks good.

00:31:38.300 --> 00:31:41.400
So zoom 14 looks fine.

00:31:41.400 --> 00:31:45.630
However, zoom 15 doesn't
look fine.

00:31:45.630 --> 00:31:49.340
On Google Maps at zoom 15, we
introduce land parcels.

00:31:49.340 --> 00:31:52.890
And in this case, the land
parcels are really distracting

00:31:52.890 --> 00:31:55.460
because they're adding a lot
of visual noise to the map,

00:31:55.460 --> 00:31:57.960
which is exactly what we
tried to avoid in the

00:31:57.960 --> 00:31:59.380
design that we did.

00:31:59.380 --> 00:32:05.210
So using the styling API, we
can simply take them off.

00:32:05.210 --> 00:32:07.560
Here you can see I've added
a style that says for

00:32:07.560 --> 00:32:11.700
administrative features, which
land parcels are a part of,

00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:12.260
turn them off.

00:32:12.260 --> 00:32:13.510
We don't need it.

00:32:16.590 --> 00:32:19.420
One way we could do that is by
appending it to all the styles

00:32:19.420 --> 00:32:21.250
that I showed you earlier.

00:32:21.250 --> 00:32:27.260
Another cleverer way is to
do it only for zoom 15.

00:32:27.260 --> 00:32:31.250
So how do you change the style
of the map for a given zoom?

00:32:31.250 --> 00:32:33.320
Here's a code snippet
that I've done.

00:32:33.320 --> 00:32:37.640
You can see what I'm doing is
I'm listening for the zoom

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:41.230
changed event, and whenever I
get that, I'm changing the

00:32:41.230 --> 00:32:44.600
styled map type that's
associated with

00:32:44.600 --> 00:32:46.660
our map type ID.

00:32:46.660 --> 00:32:48.310
I'm doing that using
an object.

00:32:48.310 --> 00:32:52.330
So I just give it the zoom to
the object, the styles per

00:32:52.330 --> 00:32:53.330
zoom object.

00:32:53.330 --> 00:32:56.390
I give it the zoom, and then
I'll get back the particular

00:32:56.390 --> 00:32:59.470
styled map type that I want.

00:32:59.470 --> 00:33:02.500
As I explained it, the adminOff
was just an addition

00:33:02.500 --> 00:33:03.790
to our previous style.

00:33:03.790 --> 00:33:08.080
So I've used a rate
concatenation in JavaScript to

00:33:08.080 --> 00:33:12.220
just add it to the one
zoom that we need it.

00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:17.080
So our one live demo.

00:33:17.080 --> 00:33:18.330
Here we have it all working.

00:33:20.680 --> 00:33:23.070
Or no.

00:33:23.070 --> 00:33:24.320
What did I click?

00:33:30.480 --> 00:33:32.595
If you wanted to see it all
again, here you go.

00:33:43.365 --> 00:33:45.670
All right.

00:33:45.670 --> 00:33:48.400
Don't click anything.

00:33:48.400 --> 00:33:52.930
So as you can see, this is a
live version of the demo that

00:33:52.930 --> 00:33:53.850
we just walked through.

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:57.350
And as I pull up, I
get constrained.

00:33:57.350 --> 00:34:00.050
I can't move any further.

00:34:00.050 --> 00:34:02.570
That's great because we then
don't need to worry about what

00:34:02.570 --> 00:34:05.820
this looks like in some
place such as Seattle.

00:34:05.820 --> 00:34:08.260
And we can zoom in.

00:34:08.260 --> 00:34:10.040
Our circles stay the same.

00:34:10.040 --> 00:34:12.960
The circles are being done with
the new symbols API we

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:15.880
launched yesterday.

00:34:15.880 --> 00:34:19.080
And we can zoom in to zoom 15
again, and now we can't zoom

00:34:19.080 --> 00:34:22.000
in anymore.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:27.150
So that's our live demo.

00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:29.670
Let's wrap up.

00:34:29.670 --> 00:34:30.340
JONAH JONES: All right.

00:34:30.340 --> 00:34:33.699
So we've given you three
principles for the design that

00:34:33.699 --> 00:34:34.510
you should remember.

00:34:34.510 --> 00:34:37.060
The first is to remove the
unnecessary information.

00:34:37.060 --> 00:34:39.790
The second is to refine the data
that you have left, and

00:34:39.790 --> 00:34:42.120
the third is to test it at
multiples zooms and regions

00:34:42.120 --> 00:34:43.739
that we've just seen here.

00:34:43.739 --> 00:34:47.590
And we've also announced some
new features, which is

00:34:47.590 --> 00:34:50.670
changing the weight of roads and
strokes, being able to set

00:34:50.670 --> 00:34:53.440
the color directly, which is
awesome and very powerful, and

00:34:53.440 --> 00:34:55.880
also being able to select
the fill and the stroke

00:34:55.880 --> 00:34:56.840
individually.

00:34:56.840 --> 00:34:59.370
And we hope that if you use all
of these new things we've

00:34:59.370 --> 00:35:01.680
announced today, then you'll be
able to create the perfect

00:35:01.680 --> 00:35:03.920
map for your site.

00:35:03.920 --> 00:35:05.210
SCOTT SHAWCROFT: We can't
wait to see what you

00:35:05.210 --> 00:35:07.330
guys come up with.

00:35:07.330 --> 00:35:08.730
Thank you for coming.

00:35:08.730 --> 00:35:11.210
We're excited for all
these new features.

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:13.200
If you have questions
we'll take them now.

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:16.140
Please use the mics because
this is being recorded.

00:35:16.140 --> 00:35:18.610
If you'd like to talk to us
personally, we're planning on

00:35:18.610 --> 00:35:21.390
heading over to the Sandbox
right after the session.

00:35:21.390 --> 00:35:24.580
In addition to us being at the
Sandbox, representatives from

00:35:24.580 --> 00:35:27.440
Trulia, Old Maps Online,
and UbiLabs--

00:35:27.440 --> 00:35:30.640
another awesome user of
custom map styling--

00:35:30.640 --> 00:35:31.730
will be there.

00:35:31.730 --> 00:35:35.510
If you liked the session, also
please drop a +1 in the box.

00:35:35.510 --> 00:35:36.760
Any questions?

00:35:40.060 --> 00:35:43.020
JONAH JONES: We have one.

00:35:43.020 --> 00:35:45.980
AUDIENCE: Can static
maps be styled?

00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:47.110
SCOTT SHAWCROFT: Yes.

00:35:47.110 --> 00:35:48.650
I got a thumbs up.

00:35:48.650 --> 00:35:52.520
AUDIENCE: OK, because I had an
